Answer:
&lt;div class="post-text" itemprop="text"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The practice I've personally observed in Go (and it's also what's recommended in the effective Go or getting started with Go tutorials) is just to define a &lt;code&gt;NewdbRepo&lt;/code&gt; function and use it for all instantation. It's implementation would look something like;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;func NewdbRepo(f, b string) *dbRepo {
    return &amp;amp;dbRepo{ foo:f, bar:b}
}
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You can't actually define a constructor as you do in most C like languages so you just gotta provide a package scoped method to do construction for you. Also, if you're not using composite literals (the initilization style I use in my NewdbRepo implementation) then you may find that alone concise enough for your needs. &lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

